'''''Hairspray''''' is a film adaptation of the [[musical theatre|Broadway musical]] of the [[Hairspray (musical)|same name]], which was in turn adapted from [[John Waters (filmmaker)|John Waters]]' [[Hairspray (1988 film)|1988 film]]. The cast includes [[John Travolta]], [[Michelle Pfeiffer]], [[Jerry Stiller]], [[Queen Latifah]], [[Amanda Bynes]], [[Christopher Walken]], [[Allison Janney]], [[Zac Efron]], and [[Paul Dooley]]. The 2007 film is produced by Zadan/Meron Productions in the [[United States]] and will be distributed by [[New Line Cinema]].

The film has been rated PG by the [[Motion Picture Association of America]] for "language, some suggestive content and momentary teen smoking."<ref>[http://www.filmratings.com/ filmratings.com/]</ref>

==Plot summary==
A film adaptation of the 2002 Broadway Tony Award-winning musical with [[John Waters (filmmaker)|John Waters]]'s alliteratively named characters about "pleasantly plump" teenager Tracy Turnblad ([[Nicole Blonsky|Nikki Blonsky]]) and her plan to integrate 1962 Baltimore by first trying to integrate the local dance show The Corny Collins Show, whose ruling queen is the bratty Amber von Tussle ([[Brittany Snow]]) and king is super-cute Link Larkin ([[Zac Efron]]). After becoming a council member and a making a big impression, she joins with local black DJ Motormouth Maybelle ([[Queen Latifah]]), her own mother Edna ([[John Travolta]]), her best friend Penny Pingleton ([[Amanda Bynes]]), and some of the town to fight back against Amber and her arrogant anti-integrationist mother Velma ([[Michelle Pfeiffer]]). The film features songs from the original Broadway show as well as original songs written by [[Thomas Meehan (writer)|Thomas Meehan]] and [[Marc Shaiman]]. The film also stars [[Christopher Walken]] as Tracy's father Wilbur, [[Allison Janney]] as Penny's paranoid mother Prudy, [[Paul Dooley]] as the WYZT TV station co-owner Mr. Spritzer, and [[James Marsden]] as The Corny Collins show host Corny Collins.

